SIMPLE: endure
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Endure
<hw>En*dure"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Endured</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Enduring</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>endurer</ets>; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) +
<ets>durer</ets> to last. See <er>Dure</er>, <pos>v. i.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Indurate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To continue in the same state
without perishing; to last; to remain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their verdure still <qex>endure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He shall hold it [his house] fast, but it shall not
<qex>endure</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Job viii. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To remain firm, as under trial or suffering; to
suffer patiently or without yielding; to bear up under adversity; to
hold out.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Can thine heart <qex>endure</qex>, or can thine hands be strong in
the days that I shall deal with thee?</q> <rj><qau>Ezek. xxii.
14.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endure</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Endure
<hw>En*dure"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To remain firm
under; to sustain; to undergo; to support without breaking or yielding;
<as>as, metals <ex>endure</ex> a certain degree of heat without melting;
to <ex>endure</ex> wind and weather.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Both were of shining steel, and wrought so pure,⟦br⟧
As might the strokes of two such arms <qex>endure</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bear with patience; to suffer without opposition
or without sinking under the pressure or affliction; to bear up under;
to put up with; to tolerate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will no longer <qex>endure</qex> it.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore I <qex>endure</qex> all things for the elect's sake.</q>
<rj><qau>2 Tim. ii. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How can I <qex>endure</qex> to see the evil that shall come unto
my people?</q> <rj><qau>Esther viii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To harden; to toughen; to make hardy.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Manly limbs <qex>endured</qex> with little ease.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To last; remain; continue; abide; brook; submit
to; suffer.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endurement</ent>⟦br⟧
